    <h1 class="article-title">From Red to Green: Building a DevSecOps Pipeline That Actually Blocks Vulnerabilities</h1>
    
    <div class="article-meta">
        <i class="far fa-calendar-alt"></i> March 15, 2025 &nbsp;•&nbsp; 
        <i class="far fa-clock"></i> 12 min read &nbsp;•&nbsp; 
        <i class="fas fa-tag"></i> DevSecOps, CI/CD, GitHub Actions, Automation
    </div>

    <p><strong>By Ashad Ali — Penetration Tester & Application Security Analyst at Bank AL Habib</strong></p>

    <blockquote>
        <strong>Introduction: The Moment I Realized "Green" Wasn't Enough</strong><br><br>
        Like many security professionals transitioning into DevSecOps, I used to think a successful pipeline meant everything turned green. Build passed? Great. Tests passed? Even better. Deploy to production? Let's go.<br><br>
        But during a recent project building an automated security pipeline for a Flask application, I learned a hard lesson: <strong>A green pipeline doesn't mean your application is secure. It just means it passed the checks you told it to run.</strong>
    </blockquote>

    <p>As a Penetration Tester at Bank AL Habib with over two years of experience in web, mobile, and API security, I've seen firsthand what happens when security is an afterthought. Vulnerable dependencies slip into production. Misconfigurations leave doors open for attackers. The goal of this project wasn't just to build a pipeline — it was to build a <strong>security gate that stops vulnerabilities before they ever reach production</strong>.</p>

    <p>In this post, I'll walk you through how I built a DevSecOps pipeline from scratch, the tools I used, the mistakes I made (and how I fixed them), and why this mindset shift is critical for anyone working in cybersecurity today.</p>

