    <h2 id="stack">1. The Stack: Tools That Make Security Automated</h2>
    
    <p>DevSecOps isn't about adding more manual steps — it's about embedding security into the automation you already have. Here's the toolkit I used for this project:</p>

    <div class="tool-grid">
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fab fa-github"></i> GitHub Actions</h4>
            <p>The orchestrator. Triggers security scans automatically on every code push, ensuring nothing slips through the cracks.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-search"></i> Semgrep</h4>
            <p>SAST — Static Application Security Testing. Scans source code for insecure patterns before the application is even built.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> pip-audit</h4>
            <p>SCA — Software Composition Analysis. Checks <code>requirements.txt</code> against known vulnerability databases.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-docker"></i> Trivy</h4>
            <p>Container Security. Scans Docker images for OS-level vulnerabilities and misconfigurations that SAST tools won't catch.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-box"></i> Docker</h4>
            <p>Consistency. Ensures the application runs the same way in development, testing, and production.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-flask"></i> Flask</h4>
            <p>The target. Simple Python Flask app intentionally running an older version (2.0.0) to simulate real-world legacy code.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="process">2. The Process: Building the Pipeline Step-by-Step</h2>

    <h3>Step 1: The Code (With Intentional Flaws)</h3>
    <p>I started with a basic Flask app. To test the pipeline's effectiveness, I intentionally used an outdated version of Flask in <code>requirements.txt</code>:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>requirements.txt</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>flask==2.0.0</code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-box">
        <strong>Why?</strong> Because I wanted the dependency scanner to fail. If the pipeline doesn't catch known vulnerabilities, it's useless.
    </div>

    <h3>Step 2: Static Analysis (SAST)</h3>
    <p>I integrated Semgrep into the workflow to scan for code-level issues:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>YAML</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>- name: Run SAST
  run: semgrep --config=auto .</code></pre>
    </div>

    <p>This step ensures that insecure coding patterns are caught early, long before deployment.</p>

    <h3>Step 3: Dependency Scanning (SCA)</h3>
    <p>Next, I added pip-audit to check for vulnerable libraries:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>YAML</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>- name: Run Dependency Scan
  run: pip-audit</code></pre>
    </div>

    <p>This is where the pipeline initially failed — and that was a <strong>good thing</strong>.</p>

    <h3>Step 4: Containerization</h3>
    <p>I created a Dockerfile to package the application:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>Dockerfile</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>FROM python:3.9-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

EXPOSE 5000

CMD ["python", "app.py"]</code></pre>
    </div>

    <h3>Step 5: Container Scanning</h3>
    <p>Finally, Trivy scans the built image for OS and package vulnerabilities:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>YAML</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>- name: Scan Docker Image
  uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@master
  with:
    image-ref: 'devsecops-app'</code></pre>
    </div>

    <h2 id="oops">3. The "Oops" Moments: Mistakes I Made (And How I Fixed Them)</h2>

    <p>No project goes smoothly the first time. Here are the real-world hurdles I faced during this build:</p>

    <h3>Mistake 1: The Hidden Folder Mystery</h3>
    
    <div class="mistake-box">
        <h4>The Problem</h4>
        <p>I created the <code>.github/workflows</code> directory for my pipeline, but when I ran <code>ls</code> in the terminal, the folder didn't show up. I thought I had made a mistake in the path.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fix-box">
        <h4>The Fix</h4>
        <p>In Linux, folders starting with a dot (<code>.</code>) are hidden by default. I had to run <code>ls -la</code> to see it. Once I realized this, I ensured the folder was correctly added to Git:</p>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>Bash</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>git add .github
git commit -m "Add GitHub Actions pipeline"
git push</code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-box">
        <strong>Lesson:</strong> Always check for hidden files when debugging path issues in Linux.
    </div>

    <h3>Mistake 2: When "Red" Is Actually Good</h3>

    <div class="mistake-box">
        <h4>The Problem</h4>
        <p>After pushing my code, the GitHub Actions pipeline turned red (failed). My first instinct was panic — did I break something?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fix-box">
        <h4>The Reality</h4>
        <p>The pipeline failed because <code>pip-audit</code> detected vulnerabilities in the old Flask version. The exit code was 1, which told GitHub Actions to stop the process.</p>
    </div>

    <p>This wasn't a bug; it was a feature. The security gate was working exactly as intended. I upgraded the dependencies:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>Bash</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>pip install --upgrade flask
pip freeze > requirements.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Fix vulnerable dependencies"
git push</code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-box">
        <strong>Lesson:</strong> A failed pipeline means your security controls are active. Don't bypass them — fix the code.
    </div>

    <h3>Mistake 3: The "Green" Misconception</h3>

    <div class="mistake-box">
        <h4>The Problem</h4>
        <p>Once the pipeline turned green, I assumed my application was live on the internet. I tried to access it via a public URL, but nothing loaded.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fix-box">
        <h4>The Reality</h4>
        <p>A green pipeline means the code passed validation — it doesn't mean it's deployed. I hadn't added a deployment step (CD) yet, only integration (CI).</p>
    </div>

    <p>To access the app, I had to run it locally using the built Docker image:</p>

    <div class="code-block-wrapper">
        <div class="code-header">
            <span>Bash</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        </div>
<pre><code>docker run -p 5000:5000 devsecops-app</code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-box">
        <strong>Lesson:</strong> CI validates; CD deploys. Understand the difference before assuming your app is live.
    </div>

    <h2 id="impact">4. Real-World Impact: Why This Matters in Banking & Enterprise</h2>

    <p>Working in banking security, I see the pressure to release features quickly. But speed without security is technical debt waiting to explode.</p>

    <h3>Traditional DevOps vs. DevSecOps</h3>

    <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Traditional DevOps</th>
                <th>DevSecOps (This Project)</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>Developer pushes code → Pipeline builds and deploys → Security team scans later (maybe) → Vulnerability found in production → <strong>Panic</strong></td>
                <td>Developer pushes code → Pipeline scans for security issues first → If vulnerabilities exist → <strong>Block deployment</strong> → Developer fixes issue → Push again → Only secure code reaches production</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>In a regulated environment like banking, this <strong>shift-left approach</strong> isn't just best practice — it's compliance. It prevents scenarios where a vulnerable library like Log4j makes it into a live banking app because no one checked the dependencies before deployment.</p>

    <h2 id="takeaways">5. Key Takeaways for Aspiring DevSecOps Engineers</h2>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Security Gates Must Be Enforced:</strong> A scan that doesn't block a build is just a report. Use exit codes to fail pipelines on high-severity issues.</li>
        <li><strong>Understand Your Tools:</strong> Know the difference between SAST (code), SCA (dependencies), and Container Scanning (OS). Each covers a different risk layer.</li>
        <li><strong>Embrace Failure:</strong> A red pipeline is a learning opportunity. It means you caught a bug before a hacker did.</li>
        <li><strong>Automation Is Key:</strong> Manual security reviews don't scale. Automate everything you can in the CI/CD process.</li>
        <li><strong>Green ≠ Live:</strong> Always verify your deployment steps. A successful build doesn't guarantee a running application.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="next">6. What's Next? From CI to CD</h2>

    <p>This project was just the beginning. Now that the security gates are in place, the next step is <strong>Continuous Deployment (CD)</strong>. I plan to integrate this pipeline with AWS (using LocalStack for testing) to automatically deploy validated images to secure environments.</p>

    <p>Additionally, I'm exploring <strong>AI-driven security automation</strong> (similar to tools like KinoSec.ai) to enhance vulnerability detection and reduce false positives. My recent work on an <a href="#">AI-Powered Nuclei Template Recommendation Engine</a> has shown me how LLMs can prioritize scans based on context, and I plan to bring that intelligence into this pipeline.</p>

    <h2 id="conclusion">7. Conclusion: Build Your Own Gate</h2>

    <p>DevSecOps isn't about buying expensive tools — it's about <strong>changing your mindset</strong>. Security shouldn't be a checkpoint at the end of the road; it should be the guardrail along the entire journey.</p>

    <p>If you're a developer, start adding security scans to your local workflow. If you're a security analyst, learn how CI/CD pipelines work. The future belongs to professionals who can bridge the gap between code and security.</p>

